<div>
What are Sections?

Sections are layout boxes that will extend to the full 100% width of the browser window, no matter how wide it is. You can add content and styles to them that you would like to stretch across the entire window.

Tip: If you donâ€™t want your main page content to stretch across the entire width of the browser window on larger displays, and want it centered like the above image, drop a Container inside of your Section, and put your content inside of that.

Learn more about using Sections:

Read our help guideWatch a video tutorial
<div>
What are Containers?

Containers are layout boxes that are set at 940px wide on larger displays (like a computer), and keep your main content centered in the middle of the page. However, for smaller devices (like phones and tablets), they extend to the full width of the screen.

Without a container:
With a container:

Learn more about using Containers:

Read our help guideWatch a video tutorial
What are Columns?

Columns let you create sections of content that site side-by-side in your main website display. You can choose how many you want, and what size you would like them all to be. You can also decide how they should behave on smaller-screen devices -- such as stacking on top of each other instead of staying side-by-side.

Tip: By default, Column rows will span across the entire space that you add them to. So if you donâ€™t want them stretching to the entire width of the browser window on larger displays, you can add a Container first, and then put the Columns inside of that.

Learn more about using Columns:

Read our help guideWatch a video tutorial
<div>
What are Blocks?

Blocks are really just empty boxes for you to build with. You can add other content elements (like text, images, other blocks, etc.) inside of them, and you can add styles to them (like defining their size, position, backgrounds, borders, typography, etc.) as well!

<a>
What are Link Blocks?

Link Blocks are very similar to normal Blocks -- you can add content to them and style them however you like -- except that they behave as links as well. So your site visitors will be able to click on them to either go to another website, scroll to a different section of your page, send an email, or call a phone number.

<a>
What are Buttons?

Buttons are simple objects that your site visitors will be able to click on to either go to another website, scroll to a different section of your page, send an email, or call a phone number. You can change the text inside of buttons, but canâ€™t add any other content elements inside of them. You can still style them any way you want, though!

Tip: If you want a clickable â€œbuttonâ€ with more than just text inside, you can use a Link Block instead. They can hold many more types of content, such as images, and can be styled to look like buttons if you want as well.

Learn more about using Buttons:

Watch a video tutorial
<ul/ol>
What are Lists?

Lists give you the ability to add sets of elements that belong together in a group (like links in a navigation menu, for instance), to add helpful structure for your site. This structure really helps machines -- like search engines and screen-readers -- better understand the content and structure of your site and present it to visitors.

The List element is the overall container for your list, which you can then add List Items by dragging them into this List item from the Add panel. You can also set whether or not this list has an important/particular order (like a numbered list) or not, and if you want bullets/numbers to be displayed next to each item.

<li>
What are List Items?

List Items are blocks of content that can be added to existing List elements by dragging them in from the Add Panel. You can then add any content you would like to them -- such as Links (for nav menus), Images, etc.

Tip: By default, List Items will be stacked on top of one another. If you want them to sit side-by-side, add a class and change their Display property to Inline-Block.
<h1>
What are Headings?

Headings are important pieces of text that can be used to break up and provide hierarchy to your text content. You should use them for titles, section headings, and subheadings within your page. You can give each Heading one of six Types -- H1 through H6 -- which should be used in order of importance or hierarchy of the headings on your page. You can also create special styles for all of the Headings on your page, and/or specific styles for individual Headings as well.

Tip: Headings play a really important role in influencing how search engines treat your site. Search engines use Headings to determine the most important themes of your page content, to figure out how well your site might match up with the words/terms people are use when searching the web.

Learn more about using Headings:

Watch a video tutorial
<p>
What are Paragraphs?

Paragraphs are text elements for the main, multiple-sentence, text content of your page. You can define the styles for all of the Paragraphs on your site (for example if you want the text in all of the Paragraphs on your page to look the same), and/or specific styles for individual Paragraph elements as well.

Learn more about using Paragraphs:

Watch a video tutorial
<a>
What are Text Links?

Text Links are pieces of text that your site visitors will be able to click on to either go to another website, scroll to a different section of your page, send an email, or call a phone number. You can define styles for all of your links -- even what they look like when visitors hover over or click on them -- as well.

<div>
What are Text Blocks?

Text Blocks are really just completely generic text boxes for your site. For example, if you have text you want to add to your site but itâ€™s not really a Heading, Paragraph, or Link, then you can just add it in as a generic Text Block -- and style it any way you want.

Learn more about using Text Blocks:

Watch a video tutorial
<img>
What are Images?

Images are graphics or photos that you can upload to display on your page. When you add an Image element, you can upload an image file from your computer. Once your image has been added, you can create classes and styles for it as well.

Tip: You can upload Retina / Hi-DPI optimized images as well, and if you check the @2x box for your image, Webflow will automatically make the appropriate adjustments to the image for the users screen resolution.

Learn more about using Images:

Watch a video tutorial
<div>
What are Videos?

Videos are super-easy to add in Webflow. Once you drag and drop a Video element into your page, you will be asked to enter the URL for where the Video is currently hosted online -- so you can just copy and paste the Video URL from YouTube, for instance. Once your video has been added, you can create classes and styles for it as well.

Learn more about using Videos:

Watch a video tutorial
<form>
What are Form Blocks?

Forms let your visitors input information into your site and submit it to you. Form Blocks are the containers that hold all of the different elements (Input fields, Drop Downs, Buttons, etc.) for your forms. You must add Form Blocks before any other form element, because form elements can only be added inside of Form Blocks. All form submissions on your site will be saved in your Site Settings (with limitations , and you can set up email notifications there as well.

Tip: There are also three states for Form Blocks that you can design: the Normal form state, a Success state that is displayed if a visitor successfully submit their info, and an Error state that is displayed if a visitor tries to submit their form and something goes wrong. Double-click on a Form Block to switch between these states.

Learn more about using Form Blocks:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<label>
What are Labels?

Labels are text blocks in forms that provide descriptive text for the different form elements, to help your visitors understand what each field is for. Once added, you can control how the Label text looks by creating and editing styles as well.

Learn more about using Form Labels:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<input>
What are Inputs?

Inputs are basic, single-line, text input fields that you can use to collect small pieces of information from visitors -- such as names, email addresses, etc. You can create classes and styles to control the look and feel of Inputs as well.

Tip: You can also add placeholder text, which will be displayed initially inside of the Input before the visitor starts adding in their own information, helping them better understand what they should put into each field.

Learn more about using Inputs:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<textarea>
What are Text Areas?

Text Areas are larger fields for collecting longer, multi-line text entries from users -- for example, a message in a â€œcontact usâ€ form. You can create classes to change the size, and styles of Text Areas to look however you like, as well.

Tip: You can also add placeholder text, which will be displayed initially inside of the Text Area before the visitor starts adding in their own information, helping them better understand what they should put into each field.

Learn more about using Text Areas:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<select>
What are Select Fields?

Select Fields represent controls with pre-defined sets of options for visitors to choose from when filling out your forms. You have full control over the different choices available in each Select Field.

Tip: You can also make Select Fields that allow visitors to select multiple choices at the same time. The displayed field looks and works a little differently, but the flexibility is there for you to use if you need it!

Learn more about using Select Fields:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<input>
What are Checkboxes?

The Checkbox field allows you to add a clickable checkbox to your form. These can be used for common Yes/No questions, or include a list of many to have your user to select all that apply. You can also change the settings so that certain checkboxes are checked when the page loads.

Learn more about using Checkboxes:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<input>
What are Radio Buttons?

Radio Buttons allow your user to select a single item from a list of multiple options. Listing multiple Radio Buttons alongside each other will allow your user to select one of the options (not multiple, like Checkboxes allow for). This is optimal when you need a user to only select one of the options, like a Yes or No question.

Learn more about using Radio Buttons:

Read our help guideWatch a video
<input>
What are Form Buttons?

Form Buttons are the buttons that visitors to click on to submit the information they have added in your forms to you. You can create classes to size, position, and style Form Buttons and the text inside of them (even how they look when hovered or pressed).

Learn more about using Form Buttons:

Read our help guideWatch a video
What are Tabs?

Tabs is a Webflow widget that allows you to easily add and style responsive tabs on your website. Tabs can be used to create a variety of different tab-related designs, including some of the examples that you can find here.

Learn more about using Tabs:

Read our help guideWatch a videoTabs Example Page
What are Facebook Buttons?

Facebook Buttons allow you to create a super simple way for people to Like your site and share it with their friends and family on Facebook. You can specify the URL, and choose from three different standard layouts as well.

What are Twitter Buttons?

Twitter Buttons give your visitors a way to spread the word about your site on Twitter. You can choose whether the button lets them Tweet about your site, or Follow your account on Twitter. You can also choose from different standard display options and layouts as well.

What is a Google+ Buttons?

Google+ Buttons give your visitors a way to share your site with others on Google+. There are a number of different layout and display settings to choose from, as well.

What are Maps?

The Maps widget lets you add interactive maps to your site. You can specify the location you would like highlighted, and different display options as well.

Tip: A cool trick with Map widgets is that you can actually change where the location is displayed in the Map panel by creating a class and changing the padding of the Map object -- if you donâ€™t want to location in the center of the Map by default.
What are Embeds?

Embed elements allow you to add in custom blocks of HTML code into your sites. So these objects are super-flexible, and can be used for a number of different things. For example, if you found/created a special object/widget somewhere else that allows you to copy and paste a small chunk of code to embed it into your own websites, you could use an Embed element to add it to your Webflow site.

Tip: As you advanced folks can probably imagine, you can do some super cool things with Embed elements and JavaScript code as well -- adding script code into Embed elements and Custom Code to your siteâ€™s Header in the Site Settings page. Note that most <script> embeds will only appear once the site has been Published or Exported, however, and not while you are actually designing the site.
What are Navbars?

A Navbar is an easy-to-use, pre-built set of elements that give you a responsive header and/or navigation menu for your site. When you drag it in, it will automatically have a place for you to add your logo image or brand on the left, and a set of menu links on the right.

The Navbar menu is special though, because you can set it to switch to an expandable/collapsable menu on smaller devices and screens! You can style every aspect of the navbar, and add or remove any elements you want to make it fit your site.

Learn more about using Navbar:

Read our help guideWatch a video
What is a Lightbox?

The Lightbox feature is a component used to display either images (including captions) or video inside a modal dialog that will present the media in a full-screen view.

This makes a lightbox a great method in which to present your media in its highest form, allowing the user to view both images and video at a larger size and in a gallery setting that will fill most of the screen.

Lightbox will also work well on all devices, making it easy to display your media for desktop, tablet and mobile screens.

View our Support GuidesWatch a Video
What are Sliders?

Sliders are powerful elements that you can use to add image galleries, slideshows, rotating content elements, and similar dynamic components to your sites. You can add as many slides as you want, customize the transitions, style the arrows, and more. You can also control how they behave responsively on different devices as well.

Learn more about using Sliders:

Read our help guideWatch a video

OK

Inline elements cannot have top or bottom margin because they flow with inline text.

Change the Display style to 'Inline Block' or 'Block' (under Advanced) to enable top and bottom margin.

Webflow automatically handles the container width to make it fit different devices.

Webflow automatically handles the container margins to make it fit different devices.

Grid containers should not be floated.

Changing column margins can break the Webflow responsive grid system. Padding is recommended instead.

This grid column gets its width automatically from the Webflow responsive grid system.

Instead of specifying an exact width, you should change the column configuration in the Settings tab.

Floating for grid colums is automatically handled by Webflow.

The top padding is automatically calculated in order to make this video responsive.

Float has no effect for elements that have absolute or fixed position.

The opacity should not be set for the body, because it will affect every element on the page.

Also, Chrome and Firefox browsers on Android phones render pages incorrectly when the body is partially transparent.

The entire body element should not be transformed.

The body can't be floated.

Since the body is the outer most element, its width is automatically handled by the browser.

The body element's Display style is read-only.

The body element's Position style is read-only.

Transitions are disabled on hover/pressed/focus states.

Instead, add a transition on the default (non-state) class.
